{{Nihongo|'''''Gyōkū Maru'''''|暁空丸}} was a {{GRT|6,854}} [[cargo ship]] that was built in 1941 as '''''Empire Dragon''''' by [[Hong Kong and Whampoa Dock|Hong Kong & Whampoa Dock Co Ltd]], Hong Kong for the [[Ministry of War Transport]] (MoWT). She was seized by the Japanese in 1942 and completed as ''Gyōkū Maru'', serving until September 1944 when she was torpedoed and sunk by {{USS|Thresher|SS-200|6}} in the [[Yellow Sea]].
==Description== The ship was built in 1941 by [[Hong Kong and Whampoa Dock|Hong Kong & Whampoa Dock Co Ltd]], Hong Kong.<ref name=Ships>{{cite book |last1= Mitchell |first1=W.H. |last2=Sawyer |first2=L.A. |year=1995 |title=The Empire Ships |page=not cited |publisher= Lloyd's of London Press Ltd |location= London, New York, Hamburg, Hong Kong |isbn=1-85044-275-4}}</ref><!-- She was yard number xxx.<ref name=xxxx/> -->
The ship was {{convert|430|ft|m}} long, with a beam of {{convert|57|ft|m}}.<ref name=Mariners>{{cite web |url=http://www.mariners-l.co.uk/EmpireD.html |title=EMPIRE – D – E |publisher=Mariners |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref><!-- She had a depth of {{convert|xx|ft|x|in|m|2}} and a draught of {{convert|xx|ft|x|in|m|2}}.--> She was assessed at {{GRT|6,854}}.<ref name=Ships/> <!--x,xxx [[net register tonnage|NRT]]. Her [[deadweight tonnage|DWT]] was x,xxx.<ref name=xxxx/>-->
The ship was propelled by a <!--xxx [[nominal horsepower|nhp]] -->[[triple expansion steam engine]].<ref name=Ships/><!--, which had cylinders of {{convert|xx|in|cm}}, {{convert|xx|in|cm}} and {{convert|xx|in|cm}} diameter by {{convert|xx|in|cm}} stroke. The engine was built by [[builder]], [[location]]. It drove a single screw propeller and could propel the ship at {{convert|xx|kn|km/h}}.<ref name=xxx/>-->
==History== ''Empire Dragon'' was launched on 6 December 1941.<ref name=Ships/> In 1942,<ref name=Mariners/> she was seized by the Japanese in an incomplete state and completed as ''Gyōkū Maru''.<ref name=Ships/>
On 22 August 1944, she was part of Convoy Namo 103 carrying evacuating civilians from [[Okinawa]] and attacked by [[USS Bowfin (SS-287)|USS ''Bowfin'']]. The fellow ship ''[[Tsushima Maru]]'' was sunk, but ''Gyōkū Maru'' escaped.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.bowfin.org/submarine/36/132-tsushima-maru |title= Tsushima Maru Sinking |publisher = USS Bowfin Submarine Museum & Park |accessdate =12 July 2011}}</ref>
On 18 September 1944, ''Gyōkū Maru'' was torpedoed and sunk by {{USS|Thresher|SS-200|6}} in the [[Yellow Sea]] ({{coord|35|02|N|124|24|E}}).<ref name=Mariners/><ref>{{Cite book|script-title=ja:船舶輸送間における遭難部隊資料（陸軍）|trans_title= Data on disaster units during ship transport (Army) |url= http://www.jacar.go.jp/DAS/meta/listPhoto?IS_STYLE=eng&ID=M2008061910150828926 |language= Japanese |year= 1946 |page = 17/50 of scanned image |publisher= Demobilization Agency Second Demobilization Department (復員庁第二復員局) |accessdate= 12 July 2011 }}</ref>
